  --- guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Installation.scala
  package org.specs2
  The recommended way to install $specs2 is via [sbt](http://scala-sbt.org).
  First you need to [install sbt itself](https://www.scala-sbt.org/release/docs/Setup.html) then you need to add the specs2 dependency:
  libraryDependencies += "org.specs2" %% "specs2-core" % "$BUILD_VERSION" % "test"
  libraryDependencies += "org.specs2" %%% "specs2-core" % "$BUILD_VERSION" % "test"
  // the regular expressions used in many specs2 matchers using strings
    testImplementation "org.specs2:specs2-core_3:$BUILD_VERSION"
    testImplementation "org.specs2:specs2-core_3:$BUILD_VERSION"
  Depending on the $specs2 features you want to use you will need to add more dependencies to your build:
   `specs2-matcher-extra`  | for the optional $specs2 matchers
   `specs2-html`           | to export specifications as html
   `specs2-form`           | to create html form-like specifications (experimental)
   `specs2-junit`          | to run specifications as JUnit tests
   `specs2-scalacheck`     | to use ScalaCheck properties in specifications (see the [ScalaCheck project](https://github.com/typelevel/scalacheck))
   `specs2-cats`           | for the [cats](https://github.com/typelevel/cats) matchers (see [specs2-cats](https://github.com/etorreborre/specs2-cats))
   `specs2-scalaz`         | for the [scalaz](https://github.com/scalaz/scalaz) matchers (see [specs2-scalaz](https://github.com/etorreborre/specs2-scalaz))
  Note: the `specs2-core` jar depends on 3 other $specs2 jars:
   `specs2-fp`             | utility classes for functional programming
   `specs2-common`         | utility classes for text, collections, xml,...
   `specs2-matcher`        | common $specs2 matchers. They can be used as a stand-alone library with [JUnit](http://junit.org)
  
  --- guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Start.scala
  ERR HTTP Error 404: Not Found
  
  --- guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Running.scala
  ERR HTTP Error 404: Not Found
  
  --- build.sbt
  import com.typesafe.tools.mima.core._
  lazy val specs2 = project
      name := "specs2",
      core.jvm,
      junit.jvm,
      core.js,
      junit.js,
      core.native,
  lazy val specs2Settings = Seq(
    organization := "org.specs2",
    homepage := Some(url("https://github.com/etorreborre/specs2")),
    specs2ShellPrompt,
    specs2Settings ++
    specs2Settings ++
        // This was needed to fix a warning (see https://github.com/etorreborre/specs2/commit/343bf6d5425733f89c5a3f1e237b39e37a3205a8)
        ProblemFilters.exclude[DirectMissingMethodProblem]("org.specs2.execute.Result.*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[DirectMissingMethodProblem]("org.specs2.matcher.ExceptionMatchers*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[MissingClassProblem]("org.specs2.matcher.ExceptionMatchers*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[DirectMissingMethodProblem]("org.specs2.matcher.Try*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[MissingClassProblem]("org.specs2.matcher.Try*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[MissingTypesProblem]("org.specs2.matcher.Try*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[IncompatibleResultTypeProblem]("org.specs2.matcher.Try*"),
        ProblemFilters.exclude[DirectMissingMethodProblem]("org.specs2.reporter.HtmlBodyPrinter.printStatistics"),
